{"id":"linear-functions","locale":"en","nextCourse":"logic","prevCourse":"graph-theory","title":"Linear Functions","description":"Input, Output and Graphs, Slope and Intercept, Parallel and Perpendicular Lines, Systems of Equations","color":"#F15E19","level":"Foundations","icon":"/content/linear-functions/icon.png","hero":"\\content\\linear-functions\\hero.jpg","goals":16,"sections":[{"id":"graphs","title":"Input, Output and Graphs","locked":true,"url":"/course/linear-functions/graphs","steps":["step-0"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"slope-intercept","title":"Slope and Intercept","locked":true,"url":"/course/linear-functions/slope-intercept","steps":["slope","questions-1","intercept","equation","equation-1","questions-2"],"goals":16,"duration":15},{"id":"parallel-perpendicular","title":"Parallel and Perpendicular Lines","locked":true,"url":"/course/linear-functions/parallel-perpendicular","steps":["step-7"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"systems","title":"Systems of Equations","locked":true,"url":"/course/linear-functions/systems","steps":["step-8"],"goals":0,"duration":5}],"steps":{"step-0":{"id":"step-0","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-0\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"slope":{"id":"slope","title":"Slope","html":"<x-step id=\"slope\" goals=\"make-point slide-point blank-0 next-0\"><div class=\"theorem\"> <p><strong>Common Core Standard 8.EE.6</strong><br> Use similar triangles to explain why the slope <em>m</em> is the same between any two distinct points on a non-vertical line in the coordinate plane; derive the equation <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals mx\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi></span> for a line through the origin and the equation <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals mx plus _b_\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>b</mi></span> for a line intercepting the vertical axis at <em>b</em>.</p></div> <p>Here you can see a <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"coordinate-system\">coordinate system</x-gloss>,</span> with a straight line that goes through its <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"coordinate-system-origin\">origin</x-gloss>.</span> To get started, pick a point anywhere on the line.</p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 360px\"> <x-coordinate-system class=\"c-system\" width=\"360\" height=\"440\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-6,6,1\" crosshairs=\"no\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system><x-gesture target=\"#slope x-coordinate-system\" offset=\"63,-107\"></x-gesture></div><div class=\"grow\"> <p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"make-point\"> We can draw a right-angled triangle between this point and the origin of the coordinate system.</p><p class=\"reveal\" data-delay=\"1500\" data-when=\"make-point\"> Try sliding the point along the line: notice how different points form differently sized triangles, but they are all <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank-mc goal=\"blank-0\"><button class=\"choice\">similar</button><button class=\"choice\">congruent</button><button class=\"choice\">equilateral</button></x-blank-mc>.</span> <em class=\"lgrey reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\"> The best way to see this is to look at the two angles along the x-axis. They are always the same size, so by the <x-gloss xid=\"triangle-aa\">AA-condition</x-gloss> the triangles must all be similar.</em></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-delay=\"1500\" data-when=\"blank-0\"> Now we can use one of the results we know about similar triangles: the ratio of two of the sides is always constant. Move the point again, and watch what happens:</p><p class=\"reveal text-center\" data-delay=\"3000\" data-when=\"blank-0\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"p.y over p.x equals p.y/p.x || '???'\"><mfrac><mrow><span class=\"pill step-target green\" data-to=\"dy\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"var\"><span class=\"var\">${p.y}</span></span></span></mrow><mrow><span class=\"pill step-target blue\" data-to=\"dx\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"var\"><span class=\"var\">${p.x}</span></span></span></mrow></mfrac><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><span class=\"var\"><span class=\"var\">${p.y/p.x || '???'}</span></span></span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"slide-point\"> But the opposite is also true: any point (<em>x</em>, <em>y</em>) that satisfies this equation must lie somewhere on the line. Therefore we now have an “equation” for the line:</p><p class=\"text-center reveal\" data-delay=\"1000\" data-when=\"slide-point\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ over _x_ equals 1.5\"><mfrac><mrow><span class=\"pill step-target green\" data-to=\"dy\" tabindex=\"0\"><mi>y</mi></span></mrow><mrow><span class=\"pill step-target blue\" data-to=\"dx\" tabindex=\"0\"><mi>x</mi></span></mrow></mfrac><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></span></p><p class=\"r text-center reveal\" data-delay=\"2000\" data-when=\"slide-point\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"⇔ _y_ equals 1.5 _x_\"><mo value=\"⇔\">⇔</mo><span class=\"pill step-target green\" data-to=\"dy\" tabindex=\"0\"><mi>y</mi></span><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>1.5</mn><span class=\"pill step-target blue\" data-to=\"dx\" tabindex=\"0\"><mi>x</mi></span></span> <button class=\"next-step\">Continue</button></p></div></div> </x-step>","goals":["make-point","slide-point","blank-0","next-0"],"keywords":[]},"questions-1":{"id":"questions-1","title":"Questions  ","html":"<x-step id=\"questions-1\" goals=\"blank-0 blank-1 blank-2\"><p>It turns out that <em>every line</em> that goes through the origin of a coordinate system has an equation of the form <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals mx\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi></span>,</span> where <em>m</em> is called the <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"line-slope\"><strong>slope</strong></x-gloss>.</span></p><p>If you’re given a line, you can find the corresponding value of <em>m</em> by picking any point that lies on the line and simply dividing its <em>y</em> and <em>x</em> value. Here are a few examples:</p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank solution=\"0.5\" goal=\"blank-0\"></x-blank></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank solution=\"3\" goal=\"blank-1\"></x-blank></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank solution=\"-1\" goal=\"blank-2\"></x-blank></p></div></div> </x-step>","goals":["blank-0","blank-1","blank-2"],"keywords":[]},"intercept":{"id":"intercept","title":"Intercept","html":"<x-step id=\"intercept\" goals=\"blank-0 var-0\"><p>But what about lines that <em>don’t</em> go through the origin of the coordinate system? In that case we need one more component: we can take the line with the same slope that goes through the origin, and shift it along the <em>y</em>-axis by adding or subtracting a number:</p><svg style=\"width: 0; height: 0; position: absolute;\"><defs><marker id=\"blue-arrow\" refX=\"2\" refY=\"2\" markerWidth=\"4\" markerHeight=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M 0 0 L 4 2 L 0 4 z\" fill=\"#fd8c00\"></path></marker><marker id=\"blue-circle\" refX=\"2\" refY=\"2\" markerWidth=\"4\" markerHeight=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><circle cx=\"2\" cy=\"2\" r=\"1.5\" fill=\"#fd8c00\"></circle></marker></defs></svg><x-coordinate-system width=\"400\" height=\"320\" x-axis=\"-8,8,1\" y-axis=\"-6,6,1\" crosshairs=\"no\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system><x-gesture target=\"#intercept x-var\" slide=\"100,0\"></x-gesture><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals 2 over 3 _x_\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></span> <span class=\"var\">${sign(a)}</span> <x-var bind=\"a|0|-4,4,1\" goal=\"var-0\">${abs(a)}</x-var></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"var-0\"> As you can see above, the number added to the value of <em>y</em> is the same as the distance between the origin of the coordinate system, and the point where the line crosses the <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank-mc goal=\"blank-0\"><button class=\"choice\"><em>y</em>-axis</button><button class=\"choice\"><em>x</em>-axis</button></x-blank-mc>.</span></p></x-step>","goals":["blank-0","var-0"],"keywords":[]},"equation":{"id":"equation","title":"Equation","html":"<x-step id=\"equation\" goals=\"next-0\"><p>We now have an equation for <em>any</em> (non-vertical) line in the coordinate plane:</p><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals _m_ _x_ plus _b_\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mrow class=\"b orange\"><mi>m</mi></mrow><mi>x</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mrow class=\"b cyan\"><mi>b</mi></mrow></span>,</span></p><p class=\"r\"> where <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> and <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> are two numbers we have to fill in. As you saw before, <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> is the <strong class=\"orange\">slope</strong> of the line, and <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> is the <strong class=\"cyan\"><em>y</em>-axis intercept</strong>. <button class=\"next-step\">Continue</button></p></x-step>","goals":["next-0"],"keywords":[]},"equation-1":{"id":"equation-1","title":"Equation  ","html":"<x-step id=\"equation-1\" goals=\"blank-0 blank-1 eqn-0\"><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 360px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"360\" height=\"360\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,6,1\" no-crosshairs=\"no-crosshairs\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system></div><div class=\"grow\"> <p>If you’re given any line, like the one on the left, you can find the value of <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> by looking at the point where the line crosses the <em>y</em>-axis. In this example, <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> = <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank solution=\"2\" goal=\"blank-0\"></x-blank>.</span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\"> Similarly, you can find the slope <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> by drawing any triangle below the line, and dividing its height and base. In this example, the slope is <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> = <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank solution=\"0.75\" goal=\"blank-1\"></x-blank>.</span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-1\"> In other words, the equation of this line is</p><p class=\"text-center reveal\" data-when=\"blank-1\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"3/4 x+2\" goal=\"eqn-0\"></x-equation></p></div></div> </x-step>","goals":["blank-0","blank-1","eqn-0"],"keywords":[]},"questions-2":{"id":"questions-2","title":"Questions  ","html":"<x-step id=\"questions-2\" goals=\"eqn-0 eqn-1 eqn-2\"><p>Here are a few more exercises. Can you find the slope and <em>y</em>-intercept in each case, and write down the equation of the line?</p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"3/2 x-2\" goal=\"eqn-0\"></x-equation></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"2x+1\" goal=\"eqn-1\"></x-equation></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_y_ equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"-1/2 x+3\" goal=\"eqn-2\"></x-equation></p></div></div> </x-step>","goals":["eqn-0","eqn-1","eqn-2"],"keywords":[]},"step-7":{"id":"step-7","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-7\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"step-8":{"id":"step-8","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-8\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]}},"availableLocales":["en"],"biosJSON":"{}","glossJSON":"{\"coordinate-system\":{\"title\":\"Coordinate system\",\"text\":\"<p>A <strong>coordinate system</strong> is a two-dimensional plane that contains two perpendicular axes. Every point on the plane can be defined using two numbers (coordinates), that specify its distance from the two axes.</p>\"},\"coordinate-system-origin\":{\"title\":\"Origin of a coordinate system\",\"text\":\"<p>The <strong>origin</strong> of a coordinate system is the point with coordinates (0, 0). It is usually the point where the two axes cross.</p>\"},\"triangle-aa\":{\"title\":\"AA condition for triangles\",\"text\":\"<p>Two triangles are <strong>similar</strong> if two of their angles have the same size. This is called the <strong>AA similarity condition</strong> for triangles.</p>\"},\"line-slope\":{\"title\":\"Slope of a line\",\"text\":\"<p>The <strong>slope</strong> of a line measures its “steepness”, and is usually denoted by the letter <em>m</em>. It is the change in <em>y</em> for a unit change in <em>x</em> along the line.</p>\"}}","hintsJSON":"{\"welcome\":\"<p>Welcome to Mathigon! I’m Archie, your personal tutor. <img class=\\\"emoji\\\" width=\\\"20\\\" height=\\\"20\\\" src=\\\"https://static.mathigon.org/emoji/g